ce:section.ce:para:
The Raman spectra of CQD was presented in Fig. S2d. The two characteristic Raman peaks centered at 1386 and 1593 cm−1 correspond to the D band and G band, respectively. The G band (which has E2g symmetry) is due to the in-plane bond-stretching modes of pairs of the sp2 hybridized carbon. The D band is due to the breathing mode of k-point phonons of A1g symmetry. This mode is not present in the perfect graphitic carbon and active only when the sample contains lattice defects and disorder (Ferrari and Robertson, 2000). Besides, the intensity ratio of D band to the G band (ID
                           /IG
                           ) is about 0.6, indicating the presence of amorphous carbon with fewer defects (Qiang et al., 2019).
